The paper discusses the use of convolution kernels for image analysis and shape recognition, which falls under the computer vision sub-category (cs.CV). The paper also mentions the application of these kernels in automation and robotics, which could fall under the robotics sub-category (cs.RO). The paper also discusses the use of electromagnetic principles for the development of these kernels, which could fall under the multimedia sub-category (cs.MM) or the graphics sub-category (cs.GR). Finally, the paper mentions the ability of these kernels to work with 3D images, which could fall under the neural and evolutionary computing sub-category (cs.NE).
